<p>The most common asked FAQs re practises.</p>
<p>1. What does it mean to &lsquo;meet my prayer partner&rsquo; weekly? </p>
<p>This flows from our value of being Jesus Centred. It means you meet with someone each week to pray with. (<a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/index.php?search=1%20thessalonians%205:17&version1=51">1 Thessalonians 5:17</a>). It may be for 10 mins or longer. It is a time to pray for the other person and for them to pray for you. It may be in a lunch time, before or after a home group, or before or after church on Sunday. Whatever suits you best.</p>
<p>2. What does &lsquo;pray for each team member&rsquo; weekly mean? </p>
<p>Simply each person in your team gets prayed for by you each week, and you get prayed for by each member of your team also. It could be driving to work, before you go to sleep at night or during your quiet time. You may do it all at once or one person a day. It&rsquo;s up to you. This is something you do by yourself so you don&rsquo;t need to meet with them personally! It also flows from our value of being Jesus Centred. (<a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew%206:6;&version=51;">Matthew 6:6</a>) and our value of the Priesthood of all Believers (<a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/index.php?search=romans%2012:9-16&version1=51">Romans 12:9-16</a>)</p>
<p>3. What does &lsquo;read through an entire Gospel mean&rsquo;? </p>
<p>We believe that the word of God is vital for all Christians to have as a regular part of their life. We agree to read a Gospel each month which primarily focus on the teachings and life of Christ. This also ties in with our vale of being Jesus Centred and we will all be reading the same Gospel. You may choose to read a chapter a day or the whole book on the last day of the month. The key is that we are reading the words and life of Christ. (<a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/index.php?search=matthew%207:24&version1=51">Matthew 7:24</a>)</p>
<p>4. What does &lsquo;meet with a spiritual coach&rsquo; mean? </p>
<p>We all need to have someone speaking into our lives and someone we can discuss anything with. <a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/index.php?search=proverbs%2019:20&version1=51">(Proverbs19:20</a>). This person is not meant to be a part of YFC and should be a bit more along the Christian journey than we are. You should meet them once a term for about an hour (but it could be more) and get their input into whatever you choose to bring up with them. This person could be a church leader, another mission leader or a retired missionary.</p>
<p>5. What is a &lsquo;discipleship tea&rsquo;? </p>
<p>This may be better described as a discipleship event. The idea is that members in an area meet together for activities that promote growing in Christ - prayer, devotion, worship, fun, encouragement. However we believe they are best done in the context of a meal. Could be breakfast, lunch, dinner or supper but don't skip the food! Jesus often discussed issues of life and faith with His disciples over a meal. In the YFC mission community the members meet together over a meal to explore a life issue (usually related to one of our values) and to reflect on the Gospel for the month. The discipleship tea should include a simple meal (members can pay $3.00 - $5.00) guided sharing (thoughts from the Gospel) Interactive study (on a life issue/value) prayer, stories (about what Jesus is doing in our mission projects, lives and young people). </p>
<p>6. What does it mean to &lsquo;as a team assist with a non YFC local community service project&rsquo;?</p>
<p>YFC members are all part of the communities that we live in and are a part of. One of the values we want to be known for is &ldquo;Mission Through Service&rdquo;. We want the community to see us as people that are not only there for ourselves and our own projects but to serve the communities we are a part of. (<a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/index.php?search=philippians%202:3-4&version1=51">Philippians 2:3-4</a>). These projects might be helping with a school gala, talking to a council and cleaning up a park or beach or helping as volunteers with a local community fun day. It&rsquo;s only once a year but you can of course do more.</p>
